@startuml sync-reachability-timeline
' Why sync callers see sync_deadline_exceeded and never delivery_failed or wake_timeout.
' Source of truth: docs/src/gateways/api/async-responses.md
!include _style.puml
scale 1 as 7 pixels
hide time-axis

concise "Sync caller" as SYNC
concise "Agent delivery" as DEL
concise "Wake" as WAKE

@SYNC
0 is "request in flight" #90EE90
30 is "**t=30s: 504 sync_deadline_exceeded**\nFIRES. The only error sync sees." #FFCDD2
78 is {hidden}

@DEL
0 is "delivery: 4 attempts, 1s+5s+25s backoff" #E6E6FA
31 is "**t=31s to 71s: 502 delivery_failed**\nDEAD CODE on sync" #F5F5F5
78 is {hidden}

@WAKE
0 is "wake: waiting for Pod Ready" #FFE4B5
78 is "**t=120s: 504 wake_timeout**\nDEAD CODE on sync" #F5F5F5
120 is {hidden}

legend bottom
  One shared axis, t=0 at inbound webhook acceptance. The wake lane is cut short to fit;
  its 120s marker sits where the label starts. The polling TTL (1h) is ~30x past the right
  edge and is deliberately **not** drawn to scale.
  ====
  **Red fires. Grey is dead code on the sync path.** `syncDeliveryDeadline` (30s) expires
  before the delivery budget can finish even its fastest possible pass (31s), and
  `wakeTimeout` (120s) is 4x the deadline. So a sync caller always gets
  `504 sync_deadline_exceeded` first, and never observes the other two.
  ----
  The delivery budget is ~31s at best (every attempt fails fast on a connect error or an
  immediate non-2xx) and ~71s at worst (31s of backoff plus 4 attempts each burning the full
  10s `agentReadTimeout`). Raising `syncDeliveryDeadline` above the delivery budget is what
  makes `delivery_failed` reachable. Async mode applies no deadline, so both grey outcomes
  are reachable there as error payloads.
endlegend
@enduml
